"Northamptonshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","scotland":"Scotland"},"da":{"1045–":"1045–Afdød","1045–Female":"1045–Afdød","1040–Male":"1040–Afdød","1065–1100":"1065–1100","1025–Male":"1025–Afdød","1025":"1025","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","about 1065":"omkring 1065","1040":"1040","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","scotland":"Skotland"},"nl":{"1045–":"1045–Overleden","1045–Female":"1045–Overleden","1040–Male":"1040–Overleden","1065–1100":"1065–1100","1025–Male":"1025–Overleden","1025":"1025","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","about 1065":"circa 1065","1040":"1040","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"1045–":"1045–Deceased","1045–Female":"1045–Deceased","1040–Male":"1040–Deceased","1065–1100":"1065–1100","1025–Male":"1025–Deceased","1025":"1025","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","about 1065":"about 1065","1040":"1040","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Angus","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and Irish: habitational name from the county and earldom of Angus in Scotland, or from the Gaelic personal name <i>Aonghus</i>, said to be composed of Celtic <i>aon</i> ‘one’ + <i>gus</i> ‘choice’. This was borne by an early Celtic deity and prominent mythological figure, and a famous 8th-century Pictish king."],"variants":[{"name":"Kennis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Abbe.","Irish and Manx: shortened form <b>Mac Aenghuis</b> ‘son of <i>Aenghus</i>’ (see   Angus  ).","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metronymic from the Yiddish female personal name <i>Kene</i> (of uncertain origin) + the Yiddish possessive suffix <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Hennessy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Kieran, Declan, Brendan, Dermot, Donal, Fidelma, Fintan, Liam, Mairead, Sean Patrick.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAonghusa</b> ‘descendant of <i>Aonghus</i>’; see   Angus  , and compare   McGinnis  ."]},{"name":"Anguish","meanings":["Scottish and English: from an English mishearing of the Scottish Gaelic personal name <i>Aonghus</i>, see   Angus   and   McAninch  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud of Angus was born in 1045, in Scotland as the daughter of Maol Choluim. She had at least 1 son with Walter Glenbervie."},"et":{"1045–":"1045–Surnud","1045–Female":"1045–Surnud","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","1065–1100":"1065–1100","1025–Male":"1025–Surnud","1025":"1025","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","about 1065":"umbes 1065","1040":"1040","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1045–":"1045–Kuollut","1045–Female":"1045–Kuollut","1040–Male":"1040–Kuollut","1065–1100":"1065–1100","1025–Male":"1025–Kuollut","1025":"1025","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","about 1065":"noin 1065","1040":"1040","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"1045–":"1045–Décédée","1045–Female":"1045–Décédée","1040–Male":"1040–Décédé","1065–1100":"1065–1100","1025–Male":"1025–Décédé","1025":"1025","1045":"1045","1100":"1100","1065":"1065","about 1065":"environ 1065","1040":"1040","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","scotland":"Écosse","lifeSummary":"Maud of Angus est née en 1045, à Écosse, fille de Maol Choluim. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Walter Glenbervie."},"de":{"1045–":"1045–Verstorben","1045–Female":"1045–Verstorben","1040–Male